    "154552503": {
      "title": "A Peculiar Sample: The Selection of Slaves for the New Orleans Market",
      "abstract": "Domestic slave traders selected taller slaves for shipment to the New Orleans market in order to increase their profits. Because traded slaves made up a large share of the slaves shipped coastwise, age/height profiles constructed from the shipping manifests are biased upwards. The extent of the bias appears to be small for adult slaves but not for children; those listed on the manifests were taller than the general population of a comparable age. A great deal of work has been done to estimate the heights of American slaves from the coastwise manifests. The resulting age/ height profiles have been used to infer the age of menarche, the determinants of antebellum health conditions, the treatment of female slaves during pregnancy, the rate of infant mortality, the profit motive behind the diet of slave children, and the net nutritional status of slaves after they entered the plantation labor force. 1 In this article, we explore the relationship between the heights of slaves chosen for shipment and the motivation behind their shipment. We argue that slave traders chose taller slaves for the New Orleans market in order to increase their profits. Based on data collected from a previously unutilized source, we show that the average heights of imported slaves sold in New Orleans exceeded that of slaves imported coastwise to New Orleans. Furthermore, when we confine our analysis to the coastwise manifests, we find that the slaves shipped by traders were taller than those shipped by nontraders. Finally, we show that the effects of selection on the heights of slaves shipped by traders was greatest among the youngest slaves."
